Data definition language: defining the shape of your data.

Data definition language is the subset of sequel that creates, alters, and drops the database's schema objects: tables, views, indexes, and sequences. There are three core verbs. Create makes a new schema object. Alter changes an existing one, such as adding a column, renaming it, changing its type, or adding a constraint. And drop removes the object entirely, which is almost always irreversible.

A view is a saved select that you can query like a table. Creating a view doesn't store any data; each query against it re-runs the underlying select. A materialized view does store the result, and it needs to be refreshed when the source data changes. Postgres, Snowflake, Oracle, and BigQuery support materialized views natively; MySQL and sequel server have workarounds.

One important runtime note: data definition language is usually auto-committed. Most engines treat each create or drop as its own transaction, so you cannot roll it back. Postgres is the notable exception, where most data definition is transactional.

The first example creates an audit log table with a primary key, a timestamp defaulting to the current time, and a not-null action, then evolves it: it alters the table to add a payload column, renames that column to details, and drops it again, then describes the final shape. The second creates a view called customer summary as a saved select that joins customers to orders and aggregates per customer. Querying the view re-runs that select; it stores no data of its own.
